Combined mitigation for the hard platform hangs on Lunar Lake under
Wayland display load (crash in __xe_pin_fb_vma, BERT: fsm_state=0x10,
"FORCEWAKE stuck at value 6"). Two write paths are affected, both CPU
write batches to GPU-managed memory regions through the gunit frontend:

1. GGTT PTE writes to GSM (xe_ggtt.c). writeq() batches stall if the GT
   enters RC6 mid-batch; GuC manages RC6 autonomously via
   GUCRC_FIRMWARE_CONTROL, so runtime PM protection upstack is not
   sufficient. Hold forcewake across all PTE write batches and the
   GGTT invalidation barrier read. Based on the v1 and v2 patches by
   Nikolay Mikhaylov <sonny@milton.pro>, incorporating changes
   originally proposed by Márton Vigh (@mrtnvgh). Tested stable for
   18+ days by independent reporters.

2. DPT programming writes to stolen memory (display/xe_fb_pin.c).
   WA 22019338487_display indicates stolen memory should not be used
   for display allocations on LNL. The fbdev path respected this; the
   Display Page Table allocation did not, so DPT programming hammered
   stolen on every tiled framebuffer pin. Skip the stolen allocation
   when the WA applies and fall back to system memory. From a patch by
   Matthew Auld <matthew.auld@intel.com>.

The two fixes are complementary: forcewake covers the GSM write
batches, while the DPT change removes the unprotected CPU write batch
to stolen that no forcewake wrap covers. Wayland is the common trigger
because tiled+CCS client buffers exercise both paths on every pin.

Link: https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/drm/xe/kernel/-/work_items/7513
---
